  <span id="freeText13982150040725190926" style="display:none">Mixed feelings about this one. After the first 150 pages I was sorely tempted to give up. The story wasn't progressing and I was getting sick of reading about two characters wandering across varying landscapes while refusing to speak to each other. It felt like I was reading a travel guide instead of a novel.<br />Then, spectacularly, the story changed and Maerad found herself without Cadvan and forced to continue her quest alone. This is where the story really picked up and I found myself glad I kept at it. I think the book would have been a lot better had their separation occurred earlier, or some of the many flowery passages describing hedgerows and streams could have been omitted. Croggon writes some stunning, poetic prose but, although pretty, it really takes away from the action. So, half a star for the first half of the book, and 2.5 for the second half.</span>
